ca 1210","1180":"1180","Henstridge, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Henstridge, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1210–1226":"about 1210–1226","1200–1260":"1200–1260","1210–1226":"1210–1226","–Female":"Deceased","1240–1316":"1240–1316","1180–1225":"1180–1225","1316":"1316","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","before 1220":"before 1220","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1210":"about 1210","1180":"1180","Henstridge, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Henstridge, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sancto","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: nickname from Latin  <i>sanctus</i> ‘holy, sainted’, denoting a pious person.  Compare  Saint  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Saint","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."]}]},{"name":"Albino","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Ramon, Manuel, Ana, Carlos, Julio, Luis, Raul, Ruben, Alfonso, Andres, Angel.  Italian Pasquale, Angelo, Antonio, Carmine, Giovanni, Luigi, Sal, Santo, Saverio, Ubalda.","Portuguese, Spanish, and southern Italian:","from the personal name <i>Albino</i> (see   Albin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Albini","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Antonio, Pasquale, Aldo, Amalio, Americo, Armando, Carlo, Caterina, Claudio, Gino, Mario, Maurizio, Nichola, Nicola, Severino, Vittorio.","Italian:","patronymic or plural form of   Albino  ."]},{"name":"Albin","meanings":["English, French, and German: from the personal name <i>Albin</i> (from Latin <i>Albinus</i>, a derivative of <i>albus</i> ‘white’). In England this is generally a variant of   Alban  . The usual spelling of the French name is   Aubin  . The personal name was especially popular in Austria, Lombardy, and Savoy, where it absorbed the ancient Germanic name <i>Albuin</i> (which is composed of the elements <i>alb</i> ‘elf’ + <i>win</i> ‘friend’; compare   Alvin  ). This was the name of the Lombard leader (died 572) who made himself king of northern Italy, and also of various Christian saints, including a bishop of Brixen (Bressanone) in South Tyrol.","Galician (<b>Albín</b>): habitational name from any of the four places called Albín in Galicia (Spain), from Latin <i>(villa) Albini</i>."]},{"name":"Alvino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Pietro, Antonio, Ciro, Salvatore, Savino.  Spanish Sabino, Aurelio, Mario, Elvira, Genoveva, Gerardo, Gilberto, Guillermo, Lazaro, Luz Maria, Margarito, Maria Carmen.","Italian (Campania): from the personal name <i>Alvino</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin. Alternatively, it may perhaps be a variant of   Albino  ."]}]},{"name":"Mauger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Channel Islands (Guernsey and Jersey): from the Old French (Norman) personal name <i>Maug(i)er</i>, <i>Malg(i)er</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Madalgar(i)</i>, <i>Malger</i>, composed of the elements <i>madal</i> ‘council, meeting’ and <i>gar(i)</i> ‘spear’, or from <i>Amalgar(i)</i>, with the first element <i>amal</i> ‘capable, brave, eager’. Compare   Major  ,   Monger  , and   Munger  .","Probably also an altered form of German   Mager  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Maugeri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Ignazio, Salvatore, Angelo, Camillo, Giuseppe, Orazio, Pietro.","Italian (southern):","variant of <b>Malgeri</b>, from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Madalgari</i> or <i>Amalgari</i> (see   Mauger  )."]},{"name":"Major","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Malg(i)er</i>, <i>Maug(i)er</i>, an Old French form of ancient Germanic <i>Madalgar(i)</i> (see   Mauger  ).","Hungarian: from a shortened form of <i>majorosgazda</i> (see   Majoros  ) or a derivative of German   Meyer  .","Polish, Czech, and Slovak: from the military rank <i>major</i> (derived from Latin <i>maior</i> ‘greater’), a word related to English <i>mayor</i> and the German surname   Meyer  ."]},{"name":"Mangieri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gaspar, Mario, Angelo, Arsenio, Mafalda, Orazio, Rocco, Silvio.","Italian: variant of <b>Malgeri</b>, from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Madalgari</i> or <i>Amalgari</i> (see   Mauger  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mauger de Sancto Albino was born about 1210 as the son of Mauger de St. Aubyn II. He married Mrs Mauger de Sancto Albino before 1220, in England. They were the parents of